    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-02-20T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-02-20T13:00:00-05:00" n="164"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d164">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1487</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-02-20T19:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 20, 1915, 7 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received February 21, 2 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1656. My 1639, February 19, 10 p. m.<note n="1" xml:id="d164fn1">Not
                        printed.</note> Admiralty desires further details about American steamers
                    proceeding to England in order safeguard their passage and asks for photographs,
                    place of departure and arrival, route, etc., also, if bound for Liverpool,
                    information whether by north or south of Ireland and approximate dates.</p>
                <p>Silhouette of American Line steamers <persName>
                        <hi rend="italic">St. Paul</hi>
                    </persName>, <hi rend="italic">
                        <persName>St. Louis</persName>, New York,</hi> and <hi rend="italic"
                        >Philadelphia</hi> given to Admiralty and point of arrival and departure
                    stated to be Liverpool.</p>
                <p>I have no further information.<note n="2" xml:id="d164fn2">By arrangement with
                        the Department of Commerce, information as to the sailing of American ships
                        was thereafter regularly received and transmitted to the Ambassador in
                        Germany for communication to the Admiralty.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
